WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.480
Can you hear me well? Okay, my name is Flávia. I'm a data scientist in Mendelix, which is a company that does

00:00:08.200 --> 00:00:11.240
diagnosis of genetics diseases based in Sao Paulo, Brazil

00:00:11.240 --> 00:00:17.340
and I'm here today to talk to you about how I have used tidymodels to validate a

00:00:17.760 --> 00:00:20.120
PRS of breast cancer in Brazil

00:00:21.760 --> 00:00:22.760
So

00:00:22.760 --> 00:00:26.440
Breast cancer is the most common type of cancer for women in

00:00:27.160 --> 00:00:30.080
85% of all countries as you can see in this map

00:00:30.879 --> 00:00:35.320
Represented in pink. You can see that both Brazil and the US are among them

00:00:36.520 --> 00:00:40.599
The main risk factors for breast cancer are sex, age,

00:00:42.279 --> 00:00:45.799
Lifestyle factors such as alcohol consumption and sedentarism

00:00:46.919 --> 00:00:49.959
hormonal factors such as contraceptive pill usage

00:00:50.959 --> 00:00:52.959
family history and

00:00:53.160 --> 00:00:55.119
genetics

00:00:55.160 --> 00:00:58.360
The genetics of breast cancer became widely known after

00:00:58.840 --> 00:01:03.279
Angelina Jolie revealed that she carried a BRCA1 mutation and

00:01:04.160 --> 00:01:07.480
Decided to undergo a preventive double mastectomy

00:01:09.120 --> 00:01:16.279
BRCA1 is an example of a gene in which mutations can dramatically increase the risk of breast cancer up to about

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:22.680
80% over a woman's lifetime. That's roughly six times the general population risk

00:01:25.160 --> 00:01:28.800
Besides high-risk mutations such as in the BRCA1 gene

00:01:28.800 --> 00:01:34.320
there are also moderate risk mutations, which increase the risk by about two to threefold and

00:01:35.080 --> 00:01:37.839
They both occur in single genes

00:01:40.279 --> 00:01:42.559
Apart from them there are also other

00:01:43.559 --> 00:01:51.080
Mutations which we'll call genetic variants that have very small effects individually that but that can be

00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:56.120
Added together in what in what composes

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:03.040
Polygenic risk score or PRS. These variants are spread all over our genome

00:02:06.680 --> 00:02:10.800
So the polygenic risk score follows a normal distribution in which

00:02:11.360 --> 00:02:15.520
the majority of us will have an intermediate score, which is

00:02:16.479 --> 00:02:18.479
The same risk as the general population

00:02:18.960 --> 00:02:25.199
but some of us will have a high score due to having a lot of this small effect variants and

00:02:25.639 --> 00:02:32.240
We'll have an increased risk for breast cancer due to the polygenic risk score

00:02:33.960 --> 00:02:41.880
This variants with small effects are discovered through very large studies with hundreds of thousands to millions of people

00:02:42.520 --> 00:02:46.600
These studies are called genome-wide association studies or GWAS

00:02:47.119 --> 00:02:51.839
They are generally conducted with individuals of a single genetic ancestry

00:02:52.279 --> 00:02:55.240
Because it facilitates the discovery of this variants

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:00.479
The majority of this study so far as you can see in this plot

00:03:00.919 --> 00:03:08.119
90% of them have been conducted with individuals of European ancestry and the big problem about that is that

00:03:08.320 --> 00:03:15.399
Not all PRS is discovered in European populations can be generalized to other ancestries

00:03:15.839 --> 00:03:19.759
because especially the there are differences in

00:03:20.720 --> 00:03:24.240
frequency and effect of variants among ancestries

00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:30.160
Brazil has one of the most diverse populations in the world

00:03:31.960 --> 00:03:36.800
75% of our individuals have more have at least two

00:03:37.399 --> 00:03:42.839
Continental ancestries and these are mainly European African

00:03:43.919 --> 00:03:46.679
Native American and East Asian and

00:03:47.800 --> 00:03:52.080
Since building our own PRS from scratch was not in the radar

00:03:52.080 --> 00:04:00.559
We decided to test if some European based PRS European developed PRS could be applied to our population

